"The sea is ours": Bolivia, blocked, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Marines patrol in an armored boat in the La Paz naval headquarters.
Public buildings have a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following motorcycle: "The sea is right back to us.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout blocked Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still present, as is the desire to sail the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades: Bolivia is awaiting a decision by the International Court of Justice, which will be delivered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on a large screen across the country, hoping that the Hague court will vote in favour of the Bolivian request. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be required to negotiate the agreement on a sovereign ocean crossing to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has much to say about the decision to be made on Monday.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that there is little chance that the court will rule in favor of Chile, and that little will change, even if a positive decision is made.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no authority to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice renders its decision six months after the latest arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” explains Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And far from favoring the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have even hurt it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been diverted by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’ belligerent rhetoric undermined all the Chilean goodwill that remained, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that, it will be very complicated to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, representing Bolivia in the Hague, rejected the idea that the Court’s decision-making was abnormally rapid.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also challenged the fact that Morales — who remains to date one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The Court’s decision is an opportunity to see that we have to get rid of the past.”
