John Edward: Language skills are essential for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with new excellent exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector capable of designing and implementing a tailor-made curriculum, we see that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and build trust with people in other countries.
If you look at the excellent exam results this year, you can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade, A.
Data collected from the 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils scored highest, A in Mandarin, as did the 72% of pupils who studied German, 69% of pupils who studied French and 63% of pupils who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and youth in the future.
Languages as subjects are now organized as are science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that among employers’ difficulties in recruiting candidates, 17% are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital to preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job vacancies requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of their career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from this lasting skill in the future.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of their competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% of them did not have enough foreign language skills to conduct a conversation, while French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those in emerging economies, children will have a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Several of them will focus on classical contemporary languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the run-up to 2020, including Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever your child’s preferences, several languages will be available in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
It is clear that, at present, in a global trading environment, languages remain of paramount importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
