North Korea says disarmament will “in no case” be unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations that maintaining sanctions reinforced his distrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
At the world body's annual general meeting, Ri Yong Ho said North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we don’t see any corresponding response from the United States,” he said.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and in such circumstances it is excluded that we will be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While reiterating North Korea’s well-known criticism of Washington’s opposition to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization whereby North Korea would be rewarded if it gradually took action, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the first ever summit between a U.S. President-in-Office and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work for “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks to formally end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also rejected demands to ease severe international sanctions against North Korea.
The United States insists that North Korea first proceed to denuclearization and increase pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing “the declaration of the end of war”.
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us go down don’t know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our mistrust.”
No comment was made on the second Kim-Trump summit highlighted before the United Nations by the US leader earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the side concerned with the issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be in such a deadlock.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target North Korean missiles on North American territory after President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened last year before the United Nations to “totally destroy” North Korea, did not fail to praise this year for the courage with which Kim has applied disarmament measures, but added that much remains to be done and that sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
“It can take two years, three years, or five months; it doesn’t matter,” he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures adopted.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that “the implementation of the Security Council’s sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until complete, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to stifle funding for Pyongyang's nuclear programmes and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang saying progress had been made, but in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced its “gangster methods.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is demanding the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights the growing macho tendency of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
A professor has noticed that most students at the best university in the world do not know how to take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
In the end, a student approached me and said, "Why is this only told to me in the last year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
First delivered this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of health services at the university, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from severe lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of various interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing various objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical benefits and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not instantly change the behavior of students.
However, in our view, they have a right to know that information – in the same way that you have a right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the pride culture of “spending a night off” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having adequate, good-quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said -- even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and urged him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar curriculum before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students provide an alarm for both bedtime and waking time, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disorders.
