Germany's new warship still postponed
According to local media, the new German Navy frigate should have been put into service in 2014 to replace aging Cold War warships, but it will not be in service until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential expenses.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which cites a military spokesman, the commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the flagship of the new frigates of Baden-Württemberg, has been postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but the worrisome issues that arose after delivery compromised the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg class ships that the Navy ordered in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-aircraft missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, such as a radar, infrared and reduced acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years outside of home ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the incessant delays mean that avant-garde warships - which should allow Germany to project its force overseas - will already be obsolete when they are put into service.
Last year, the cursed frigate F125 made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
The reasons for the return were little known, but the German media mentioned a number of “software and hardware defects” that made the warship useless in case of deployment on combat missions.
The software flaws were particularly important because the Baden-Württemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, which corresponds to half of the crews of the old Bremen class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the vessel is considerably overloaded, which reduces its performance and reduces the Navy's ability to make future improvements.
It is estimated that the 7,000-ton “Rheinland-Pfalz” weighs twice as much as similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond the failures of the computer system, the price of the project as a whole - including the training of the crew - also becomes a problem.
It is said to have reached the astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), compared to 2.2 billion at the beginning.
The problems of the new frigates are of particular importance in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval force is declining.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament’s defence commission, acknowledged earlier this year that the Navy is actually “out of ships capable of deploying.”
The official said the situation had produced a snowball effect over time, as the old ships were decommissioned but no replacement ships were designated.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class could join the Navy.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research in an area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The National Trust for Scotland study will follow common pipistrels and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at Inverewe Garden, Wester Ross.
Special registration devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using handheld detectors.
Professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat screams and the activities of different species.
A map and habitat report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of grasslands and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects perches and leads to the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-killing papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight route.
In charge of protecting more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave site in Dumfries-et-Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, manager of the domain, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
“Here in Threave we have a great place for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there’s still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
It stresses the importance of checking the presence of bats before proceeding to the maintenance of properties, because by unintentionally destroying a single maternity nest, one can thus cause the death of 400 females and young, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their poles.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as for many of our species, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations right now.”
